# Database Conventions — Neon PostgreSQL via Prisma ORM

> **Prisma is the project's ORM.** All database access goes through Prisma Client. This supersedes any earlier raw-SQL/`pg`-pool convention — if you see raw `pool.query(...)` code anywhere in older docs or code, treat it as stale and port it to Prisma.

## Connection
- Use `@prisma/client`, generated from `prisma/schema.prisma`
- A single `PrismaClient` instance is exported from `src/db/prisma.ts` — import `prisma` from there; never call `new PrismaClient()` anywhere else (each instance opens its own connection pool)

```typescript
// src/db/prisma.ts
import { PrismaClient } from '@prisma/client';

const globalForPrisma = global as unknown as { prisma: PrismaClient };

export const prisma =
  globalForPrisma.prisma ??
  new PrismaClient({
    datasources: { db: { url: process.env.DATABASE_URL } },
  });

if (process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production') globalForPrisma.prisma = prisma;
```

## Query Rules (security-critical)
- **Always** use Prisma Client's query builder (`findUnique`, `findMany`, `create`, `update`, `upsert`, `delete`, ...) — this parameterizes automatically.
- **Never** build SQL strings by hand for normal CRUD.
- If a query truly can't be expressed through Prisma's API (rare — complex multi-table aggregation), use `prisma.$queryRaw` with a **tagged template literal** only. Never `prisma.$queryRawUnsafe` and never string concatenation/interpolation into a raw query.

```typescript
// ✅ Correct — Prisma query builder
const article = await prisma.article.findFirst({
  where: { id: articleId, status: 'Published' },
});

// ✅ Acceptable when the query builder genuinely can't express it — tagged template, still parameterized
const rows = await prisma.$queryRaw`
  SELECT * FROM articles WHERE id = ${articleId} AND status = ${'Published'}
`;

// ❌ DANGEROUS — never do this, defeats Prisma's protection entirely
const rows = await prisma.$queryRawUnsafe(
  `SELECT * FROM articles WHERE id = '${articleId}'`
);
```

## Schema Naming (`prisma/schema.prisma`)
| Element | Convention | Example |
|---------|------------|---------|
| Models | `PascalCase` singular | `Article`, `TechTalk`, `QuizAttempt` |
| Fields | `camelCase` in Prisma schema, mapped to `snake_case` columns via `@map` | `createdAt` → `@map("created_at")` |
| Tables (DB) | `snake_case` plural, set via `@@map` | `@@map("articles")` |
| Primary keys | `id String @id @default(uuid()) @db.Uuid` | always UUID |
| Foreign keys | `[modelSingular]Id` | `articleId`, `userId` |
| Timestamps | `createdAt`, `updatedAt`, `deletedAt` | always present, via `@default(now())` / `@updatedAt` |
| Indexes | `@@index([field])`, named implicitly by Prisma | index on `authorId` etc. |

## Core Schema (reference — do not alter without a migration)

> Neon Auth automatically maintains the `neon_auth.users` table. **Never model or manage a `User` table yourselves** — Neon Auth owns that schema. Reference it in relations via the raw `neon_auth.user(id)` foreign key using `@relation(fields: ..., references: ...)` against an unmanaged/external table (see Prisma's `previewFeatures = ["multiSchema"]` if the project spans schemas).

```prisma
// prisma/schema.prisma

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
}

datasource db {
  provider = "postgresql"
  url      = env("DATABASE_URL")
}

enum ArticleStatus {
  Draft
  Pending
  Published
  Unpublished
}

model Article {
  id          String        @id @default(uuid()) @db.Uuid
  title       String        @db.VarChar(500)
  body        Json          @default("{}")
  status      ArticleStatus @map("article_status")
  authorId    String        @map("author_id") @db.Uuid
  tags        String[]      @map("article_tags") @default([])
  createdBy   String        @map("created_by") @db.Uuid
  deletedAt   DateTime?     @map("deleted_at")
  createdAt   DateTime      @default(now()) @map("created_at")
  updatedAt   DateTime      @updatedAt @map("updated_at")

  comments    Comment[]
  likes       Like[]
  reviews     Review[]

  @@map("articles")
  @@index([authorId])
  @@index([status])
}

model Comment {
  id        String    @id @default(uuid()) @db.Uuid
  articleId String    @map("article_id") @db.Uuid
  createdBy String    @map("created_by") @db.Uuid
  body      String
  deletedAt DateTime? @map("deleted_at")
  createdAt DateTime  @default(now()) @map("created_at")
  updatedAt DateTime  @updatedAt @map("updated_at")

  article   Article   @relation(fields: [articleId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  @@map("article_comments")
}

model Like {
  id        String   @id @default(uuid()) @db.Uuid
  articleId String   @map("article_id") @db.Uuid
  userId    String   @map("user_id") @db.Uuid
  createdAt DateTime @default(now()) @map("created_at")

  article   Article  @relation(fields: [articleId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  @@map("article_likes")
  @@unique([articleId, userId], name: "uq_article_likes")
}

enum NotificationReferenceType {
  article
  tech_talk
  comment
  like
  review
}

enum NotificationType {
  success
  failure
  info
}

model Notification {
  id                  String                     @id @default(uuid()) @db.Uuid
  recipientId         String                     @map("recipient_id") @db.Uuid
  title               String                     @map("notification_title") @db.VarChar(255)
  referenceType       NotificationReferenceType  @map("notification_reference_type")
  referenceId         String                     @map("reference_id") @db.Uuid
  type                NotificationType           @map("notification_type")
  message             String
  isRead              Boolean                    @default(false) @map("is_read")
  readAt              DateTime?                  @map("read_at")
  deletedAt           DateTime?                  @map("deleted_at")
  createdAt           DateTime                   @default(now()) @map("created_at")

  @@map("notifications")
  @@index([recipientId])
}

enum TechTalkStatus {
  draft
  published
  unpublished
}

model TechTalk {
  id                String         @id @default(uuid()) @db.Uuid
  title             String         @db.VarChar(500)
  description       String?
  presenters        String[]       @default([])
  eventDate         DateTime       @map("event_date")
  slidesUrl         String?        @map("slides_url")
  youtubeIframeUrl  String?        @map("youtube_iframe_url")
  status            TechTalkStatus @default(draft) @map("tech_talks_status")
  createdBy         String         @map("created_by") @db.Uuid
  deletedAt         DateTime?      @map("deleted_at")
  createdAt         DateTime       @default(now()) @map("created_at")
  updatedAt         DateTime       @updatedAt @map("updated_at")

  @@map("tech_talks")
}

enum ReviewStatus {
  Pending
  Approved
  Rejected
}

model Review {
  id              String       @id @default(uuid()) @db.Uuid
  articleId       String       @map("article_id") @db.Uuid
  reviewerId      String       @map("reviewer_id") @db.Uuid
  feedback        String?      @map("review_feedback")
  status          ReviewStatus @map("review_status")
  createdBy       String       @map("created_by") @db.Uuid
  deletedAt       DateTime?    @map("deleted_at")
  createdAt       DateTime     @default(now()) @map("created_at")
  updatedAt       DateTime     @updatedAt @map("updated_at")

  article         Article      @relation(fields: [articleId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  @@map("article_reviews")
  // Feedback required on rejection — enforce in ReviewService (Prisma has no native
  // conditional CHECK constraint equivalent; add a raw migration CHECK constraint
  // via prisma/migrations if you need it enforced at the DB layer too)
}

model QuizAttempt {
  id            String   @id @default(uuid()) @db.Uuid
  userId        String   @map("user_id") @db.Uuid
  articleId     String   @map("article_id") @db.Uuid
  questions     Json
  answers       Json
  score         Int?
  total         Int?
  scorePercent  Decimal? @map("score_percent") @db.Decimal(5, 2)
  submittedAt   DateTime @default(now()) @map("submitted_at")

  @@map("quiz_attempts")
}
```

## Migration Rules
- Use `npx prisma migrate dev --name [description]` locally — never hand-write migration SQL unless adding a constraint Prisma's schema language can't express (e.g. a conditional `CHECK`).
- Never edit a migration file that has already been applied/committed — create a new migration instead.
- Migrations are generated under `prisma/migrations/[timestamp]_[description]/migration.sql` — treat these as generated artifacts, reviewed but not hand-edited except for the rare raw-SQL addition (documented with a comment explaining why).
- Run `npx prisma migrate deploy` in CI/production — never `migrate dev` outside local development.
- After any schema change, run `npx prisma generate` to refresh the typed client.

## Soft Delete Pattern
- Models with `deletedAt` use soft delete — never hard delete `Article`, `Review`, `Notification`, `Comment`, or `TechTalk` rows.
- All reads on soft-delete models must include `deletedAt: null` in the `where` clause.
- Admin hard-delete (Article only, Admin role) uses Prisma's `.delete()`; everything else uses `.update({ data: { deletedAt: new Date() } })`.

```typescript
// Admin soft-delete
await prisma.article.update({
  where: { id: articleId },
  data: { deletedAt: new Date() },
});
```

## Aggregation Queries (avoid N+1 — use `include`/`_count`, not per-row queries)
```typescript
// ✅ Single query with aggregation (for article listings)
const articles = await prisma.article.findMany({
  where: { status: 'Published', deletedAt: null },
  include: {
    _count: { select: { likes: true, comments: true } },
  },
  orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' },
});
```
For cross-table aggregations that don't map cleanly to Prisma's relational API (e.g. the admin dashboard's single-query summary across unrelated tables), use `prisma.$queryRaw` with a tagged template — see `analytics-dashboard-engineer`'s rules.
